column1: Before 1 November 2022, will a snap election be called for the Northern Ireland Assembly?
column6: ['Foreign Policy', 'Elections and Referenda', 'Non-US Politics']

With Truss on the way out I honestly don't see how they are going to make progress on this in the next 8 days. My previous concern was that Westminster might extend the date (28th October) as they have done in the past but NI is probably even less of a priority now than it usually is.
see above

Increasing probaility as time went by and potential election dates are already shared, all while the DUP is not moving: https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2022/oct/18/ni-likely-to-face-its-second-election-this-year-by-xmas-mps-told

Heaton-Harris has stated that if the DUP refuses to share power, he'll have to call a snap election. Heaton-Harris seems to be rigid on his call for an eventual snap election, and given that talks and negotiations aren't proceeding quickly, I doubt they'll reach an agreement in 9 days. In addition, the DUP is super strong on their position and seem to want a lot out of the negotiations. What really causes me to vote 72% yes is that the DUP also seems content with a snap election. The low likelihood of an agreement by October 31st, coupled with all parties being happy with a snap election, leads me to believe that a snap election will be likely.

While promises are kept less often then they generally should be in the realm of governance, I am confident that the UK's Secretary of State (Chris Heaton-Harris) will keep his word and call an election of the 28th. Heaton-Harris has maintained this stance for the past few months and he would look weak and indecisive if he did not call the snap election for when he planned to. While anything is possible in the political sphere, and it is possible that Heaton-Harris could be pressured to call an election on a latter date, I am nevertheless confident that a snap election will be called for on 28 October.

I think everyone involved understands that another election won't change anything and would probably further entrench current positions at a cost of millions of pounds to the taxpayer, right at the cusp of a major cost-of-living crisis. However, it seems that the DUP is intent on either having their tantrum heard by an increasingly apathetic Westminster or at the very least taking a shot at rewriting the May election result by stirring up unionist passions with their hardline stance.*
The potato crop is good this year.

Context: UK amended the Northern Ireland legislation just in February after a first DUP minister went out of office to allow for 24 weeks after the assembly first met. This would be by 28 October. Politico reports that the Northern Ireland Secretary of the UK government does not plan to amend the legislation again.

It also seems like there might be a path towards a deal between the UK and the EU on Northern Ireland, which could push the DUP to cave in before a snap election is called (even if a deal is not finalised by the end of the month). https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2022/oct/05/uk-and-ireland-to-hold-talks-on-resolving-northern-ireland-brexit-row

Initial forecast. Tired of US political questions ;-)

This doesn't seem that unlikely. Stormont has up to 24 weeks following an election to form a new executive, per the power-sharing agreement with Westminster, so the DUP always knew the deadline they were looking at. There has clearly been no progress on their side, either in terms of them moving towards resolving the situation, or a sign that their demand (the UK ditching the Northern Ireland Protocol) might be met as the new government has shown no inclination towards invoking Article 16 and has been moving closer to the EU if anything (https://www.irishtimes.com/ireland/2022/10/04/dublin-and-brussels-remain-cautious-over-britains-apparent-change-of-tone-on-ni-protocol/).
